Dinner.
Crispy chicken breast.
I'm not much of a fan of the egg, flour, breadcrumbs routine. I flattened the chicken breast. Painted it with smoked garlic mayonnaise then coated it in panko breadcrumbs. Much lighter than the normal panÃ¨. It's also good done with dijon instead of the mayo.
Then I pan fried in butter and a little olive oil.
Served with Violet potatoes. These are not just a gimmicky thing. They are really delicious.
Served with a mixture of wonderful spring leaves. Purple kale, green kale, cavalo nero, spring greens, rainbow chard and fine beans. I steamed all the leaves then tossed in smoked garlic butter.
Some fried red peppers added lovely sweetness.
Sprinkled with coriander.

Crispy Salt and Pepper ChickenÂ Â

Â #crispychicken #chinesefood #asiancooking #fakeaway

Recipe

(I chose to brine the chicken first with a mix of salt and cold water)Â 

Thinly slice 4 boneless chicken thighs
Thoroughly coat in cornflour
Add one whisked egg, and mix until chicken is covered and sticky to touch

In a bowl add approximately 120g cornflour (or potato starch for a better crisp) and 30g Custard powderÂ 

Throw the stick chicken into the bowl, and get messy!
Roll the chicken around until each piece is separate and covered again in the cornflour/custard powder mix

Deep fry the chicken at medium heat for 2 - 3Â  minutes - as this stage the chicken can be stored for later use
When chicken is needed, refry at high heat for 2- 3 minutes before tossing through â€œsalt and pepperâ€ mixture

In a pan warm 2 tbls salt, 1 teaspoon five spice, 1 tbls Szechuan green peppercorns, before crushing the mixture in a pestle and mortar
Slice and dice one onion, red chilli and redpepper

Fry onion, pepper and chilli, when softened add the refried and crispy chicken, and the spice mixtur, at this stage you may wish to add a dash of soy sauce and 1 tbls sugar for sweetness

Chicken and creamy leek risotto ğŸ˜‹â¬…ï¸
This was absolutely delicious and throughly enjoyed it, something very comforting about a bowl of risotto.
To make this I sprinkled some @schwartz.uk chicken chargrilled seasoning (1) onto a chicken breast and roast in the oven.
While that was cooking added 65g risotto rice to a pan with a small diced onion and 1 tsp @verylazyfooduk garlic. Make up 400ml stock (I used 1 @knorruk chicken stock pot mixed with boiling water) and add this to the rice a little bit at a time stirring often. After 5 minutes add in some sliced leeks (I used 2 leeks) and stir through. Keep stirring and adding stock until its all gone and absorbed by the rice. Then I stirred through 35g @philadelphia_uki lightest (1.5)  which made it silky smooth and creamy - definitely recommend doing this! Added the risotto to a bowl and sliced the chicken on top, finished with some fresh parsley - 2.5 syns total and a very happy belly, perfect ğŸ‘ŒğŸ»ğŸ˜ğŸ‘ğŸ»

REPOST from @dandyhillfarm:
There seems to be a lot of concerns and questions about chickens during the winter season, so we would like to offer a few tips that we use when the temps drop close to or below zero.

Winter can be tough on chickens, but theyâ€™re remarkably adaptable creatures and most standard breeds can naturally acclimate to the cold temps. Though, there are a few breeds that struggle; silkies, frizzles, polish, and other tiny bantams like dâ€™Uccles or seramas. They need a little bit of extra care.

A chickenâ€™s body temperature is around 106 degrees Fahrenheit and a high metabolism that helps them stay warm in the winter. When a chicken starts to get cold, it will eat more, ruffle its feathers to trap warm air, and huddle with others for warmth. Eating more speeds up their metabolism. So it is very important to keep a constant food source available to them during the cold snaps.

Single combs and long wattles, like Eggberts, are susceptible to frost bite and it happens FAST. By applying petroleum jelly or salve, you can help save them from frost bite, plus, they like the little massage too.

Offer nutritious snacks higher in fat and protien. We posted our recipe in our stories. This will provide the extra energy the chicken's body needs to keep warm.

A common mistake when winterizing your coop is that it needs to be sealed up completely. This is actually more detrimental to your birds. They need adequate ventilation in order to release the ammonia fumes created by manure and to keep bedding dry. Vents need to be high and positioned for cross air flow. Ventilation doesnâ€™t need to be complicated. Just seal up anything low, so you can eliminate drafts. A layer of straw up to a foot deep on your coop floor will help keep your chickens warmer. We prefer straw because of its ability to trap warmth in its hollow shafts. The straw will also start to breakdown, which will generate heat. For a heating element, we really like the Producers Pride brooder heat plates. Theyâ€™re safe, convenient, inexpensive, and multi-use. You can find them at @tractorsupply

Education is the key to understanding. We hope our tips are helpful.

Homemade Tandoori Chicken ğŸŒ¶ï¸ğŸ— (Recipe posted ğŸ‘‡)

Indian food is one of the most gluten-free friendly cuisines out there as the spices and sauce are naturally without wheat. Give this famous chicken dish a try, especially if you found the restaurant ones too spicy. Making it at home allows you to adjust the spice level to your preference. 

â±ï¸Prep time: 10 minutes
â±ï¸Cook time: 30 minutes 

ğŸ“„ Ingredients:
ğŸ”¸4 skinless, bone-in chicken leg quarters ğŸ—
ğŸ”¸1/2 tablespoon curry powder
ğŸ”¸1/2 tablespoon garam masala
ğŸ”¸1/2 tablespoon paprika
ğŸ”¸1/4 to 1/2 teaspoon cayenne pepper (adjust for your preferred spice level)ğŸŒ¶ï¸
ğŸ”¸1 tablespoon neutral tasting oil
ğŸ”¸1 teaspoon salt 
ğŸ”¸1 tablespoon lemon juice ğŸ‹
ğŸ”¸1/2 cup plain yogurt
ğŸ”¸2 gloves garlic, minced ğŸ§„
ğŸ”¸1/2 teaspoon minced ginger (optional)
ğŸ”¸1 drop red food coloring â™¦ï¸

Instructions:
1ï¸âƒ£ Cut slits on the chicken leg quarters
2ï¸âƒ£ In a bowl, mix together all the spices, salt with the oil, lemon juice, garlic, ginger and food coloring into a paste.
3ï¸âƒ£ Rub the spice paste evenly over the chicken leg quarters.
4ï¸âƒ£ Brush the plain yogurt over the spice rub on the chicken. Cover and marinate over night. 
5ï¸âƒ£ Arrange the chicken pieces on a baking tray, discard any extra marinade. 
6ï¸âƒ£ Preheat oven to 375F, bake until outside browns and inside is cooked through (about 25-30 minutes.
7ï¸âƒ£ Rest for 5 minutes and serve warm.

ğŸ“Higher Ground Cafe

ğŸ“Pixieâ€™s Candy Parlour

ğŸ“Monki Bistro

CINNAMON TOAST CRUNCH

Ahh yes. The famous cinnamon bun hot chocolate Iâ€™ve been seeing all over Instagram! The star of the show was definitely the cinnamon bun. The Cinnamon Toast Crunch rim was also incredible. The white hot chocolate just tasted like sweet milk to me. â­ï¸9/10

ğŸ“Yann Haute Patisserie

MADAGASCAR TROPICAL

This one was so different and so.. THICC! My brain couldnâ€™t process all the flavors that was going on, and when you dipped that crunchy palmier and took a bite.. it was like heaven! But, this isnâ€™t everyoneâ€™s favorite taste. Too much of it would definitely be overwhelming. â­ï¸10/10

ğŸ“JusFruit

RED VELVET CUPCAKE & OREO CHEESECAKE

ğŸ“Amato Gelato Cafe

NUTELLA WITH MINI BOMBOLONI

The bomboloni was SO GOOD! And the hot chocolate tasted exactly like Nutella. The whipped cream on top was thick and almost tasted like ice cream! Itâ€™s such a generic flavor, but Iâ€™m OBSESSED with Nutella.â­ï¸10/10

This is probably the thing I have made that I am most proud of thus far. These are *plum* brownies - rich and chocolatey, chewy and fudgy, and a sweet, fruity undertone. 

I peeled and seeded three plums (by slitting the skin, blanching, and then putting in ice water, pic 3), mashed them up banana bread style and then added 2 eggs, 1/2 cup oil, 3/4 cup sugar. Then, sifted together and added .7 cup of flour, 1/2 cup of cocoa powder, a pinch salt, and 1/8 tsp baking powder. I made the whole thing in my food processor, baked in an 8x8 greased pan at 350 until my tooth pick came out clean. I really hope you try them at let me know what you think! My guess is this would be easy to do with other fruit chocolate pairings like strawberry, orange, etc. I cant get over that shiny crust. Only 137 calories a square.

ğŸ“ Nomad - Surry Hills - Part 2 - Mains

I wouldnâ€™t say all of these are considered mains, but due to the chronological order that they were served, Iâ€™ve grouped them all together. Again, every single dish was absolutely stunning and vibrant with flavour!

The ribeye was the most expensive dish on the menu. It was a quality piece of steak cooked medium rare (leaning towards rare). I enjoyed the addition of salsa verde on top which helped cut through the heaviness of the dish; keeping it balanced. The waiter also recommended a side of iceberg lettuce which was actually surprisingly delicious too! It was topped with orange and their housemade shanklish (a type of cheese)!

The date glazed wagyu tongue was also amazing! The sweet glaze on the tongue contrasted well with the Smokey low notes of the tahini! The king prawn dish was great but I wouldnâ€™t say itâ€™s a essential must try by any means.

Besides the proteins we also got the burrata and zucchini flowers! One of the best burrata that Iâ€™ve tried; the sweetness of the fennel jam and that robust olive oil really complimented the lightness of the burrata! Zucchini flowers were great too, of course since there was truffle honey and pecorino! 

Part 3: desserts

-
600g grasslands ribeye, vine league salsa verde
Date glazed wagyu tongue, baharat, tahini
Vanella burrata, fennel jam, alto robust VOO
Zucchini flower, truffle honey, pecorino
North QLD king prawns, sugar loaf cabbage, roast prawn butter
For lunch I pan fried some glass noodles with veggies and all the flavorful sauces you could think of. Super easy, super healthy, super delicious!

Indonesian steamed sponge cake ğŸ˜

If you have been following, you would notice most of Indonesian traditional goodies use coconut milk. These following cakelettes are also with coconut milk ğŸ˜Š

ingredients

125 ml coconut milk, heat in microwave for 30 seconds

90 g flour

50 g sugar

1/2 tsp each BPowder and BSoda

1/2 tsp Pandan essence (screwpine) and a couple drops of green food coloring - should you be able to find Pandan paste, omit essence and food coloring

a pinch of salt

1 tsp vanilla essence

topping

1/4 c unsweetened desiccated coconut

generous pinches of salt

1 tbsp water

how to

in a bowl, mix coconut, water and salt, heat in microwave 1 minute, at 30 seconds intervals

grease molds with cooking oil, then spoon some coconut into molds

preheat steamer

mix dry ingredients then pour in wet ingredients, stir well

pour batter covering coconut and steam for 20-25 minutes

MUTTON / BEEF SAMBHAR BAZOUN (fried spices) CURRY - Ivan Pereira

INGREDIENTS:
1 kg mutton/beef with bones (cut into medium pieces and washed)
1/2 kg kuvalo (ash gourd)/beans
1 onion (sliced)
1 tsp ghee
salt to taste
vinegar to taste

To grind:

First dry roast: 
3 long byadgi chillies
5 round short chillies (motwi mirsaang)
1 tsp mustard seeds
2 tbsp heaped coriander seeds
1 tbsp heaped jeera
10 pepper corns

Fry in a little oil:
1 onion (sliced)
3-4 cloves garlic

Grind all above with:
6 tbsp fresh grated coconut (can be dry roasted before grinding, if desired)
lime size tamarind or 1 tsp tamarind paste
1 tsp turmeric powder

STEPS:
Boil or pressure cook the mutton with 1 tsp vinegar and salt till it is soft.

In a pan, dry roast the mustard seeds, coriander seeds, jeera, pepper corns, short round chillies, byadgi chilliesÂ separately. Keep it aside to cool.Â 
Heat a few drops of oil. Add the onion and fry till golden. Keep it aside to cool.
Add garlic and lightly saute. Keep it aside to cool.Â 

Add all the fried/dry roasted ingredients into a mixie jar along with coconut, tamarind, turmeric and a little water. Grind to a fine paste.Â 
Add the ground masala to the cooked mutton and mix well. Cook for 10 minutes.
Add the kuvalo/beans and bring the curry to a boil.Â 

Separately, heat ghee in a pan.Â 
Fry one onion till brown.
Add it to the curry, cover with the lid and switch off the flame.Â 
ENJOY!

If ur thinking of a Sunday roast - mums gravy chicken is the way to go.

For the marinade of one skin on-chicken you will need: 
1 skin-on chicken 
2 Tbsp of butter, melted
3 Tbsp of Maggiâ€™s Malaysian chilli sauce with garlic 
The juice of one lemon
1 whole bulb of garlic minced

Mix all the marinade ingredients in a bowl and then pour over the chicken. Be sure to put some marinade under the skin for a flavoursome chicken.

Cut a garlic bulb and lemon in half. Stuff the cavity of the chicken with half of the garlic and lemon and place the other halves in the tray to roast. 

Leave in the fridge overnight or a few hours.

Method: 
Place the oven at the highest setting and cook uncovered until the skin is brown and crispy.
Once crispy, Reduce the heat down to 180-200 degrees. 
Cover the chicken in foil and cook for a further 40 mins or until the chicken is cooked through.

Onion Gravy:
You will need to reserve some of the juices from the chicken half way through cooking. At this point also remove the garlic and lemon you roasted with the chicken.

2 Tbsp of gravy granules
3 Tbsp of chicken juices 
1 Tbsp Maggiâ€™s Malaysian chilli sauce with garlic
1 Tbsp ketchup
Water to gain ur desired consistency
And roasted lemon, garlic.

Cook all the above together in a pan until It boils. Sieve and strain into a smooth gravy. Once strained you can also add in some roasted onion slices for extra flavour.

Serve this with your favourite Sunday roast sides and enjoy!

Crickey, a year to the day since I ate at @restaurant_geranium. A serious restaurant, one for which foodie trainspotters and bucket-list warriors descent en masse clutching little red books, checking-in on Facebook and populating Instagram with a frenzy of carefully contrived images. Ahem, guilty.

Danish-born @rkgeranium, the acclaimed Nordic chef, explores natureâ€™s perpetual change and beauty. The menu moves and dances with the seasons with local ingredients the backbone to dishes, a study of history, earth, sea and home.

I remember a flurry of appetizers starting with a bowl of crispy leaves and pickled walnut leaves; cucumber water with â€œham fatâ€ and snail eggs; and a faux razor clam of which everything is edible, casing and all. There are scallops, oysters and more truffles, an excellent charred potato served with smoked butter, some seeds and seaweed. There are seasonal yellow beets and pickled celeriac, and an entire course during the halfway point dedicated to bread â€“ lots of little breads baked using ancient grains.

Home-cured meats are remarkable too, including the â€œham fatâ€ in the appetiser above and a course before dessert which takes the diner through the wine cellar and into an adjoining room where beer from Mad Fritz Brewery in the Napa Valley and thinly sliced duck breast is served.

The food is faultless, and the restaurant a neat and impressive space - lots of natural light, ironed white tablecloths, trendy shell chairs and Danish furniture by Hans J Wegner along with all of Kofoedâ€™s many awards, including his gold, silver and bronze Bocuse dâ€™Or statues.

A spectacular 360-degree view of Moscow from the 16th-floor dining room of @whiterabbitmoscow in December last year. @muhinvladimirâ€™s inventive cuisine uses Russian ingredients â€“ think coco lardo with black caviar and black bread, barley porridge with hazel grouse and morels or baked cabbage with caviar. Oh, and swan liver paÌ‚teÌ with torched marshmallow (in posting); subtle, seductive, meant only for angels, kings and the grandiose.

The food explores the development of the countryâ€™s cuisine (â€The Russian Evolutionâ€) with the gastronomic scene flourishing, and the idea of frozen food from the Bloc being shaken away. Many of the staple Russian  ingredients remain - cabbage, crab, bread, root veg - and while the producers and the markets have been in the city for a long time, itâ€™s the application thatâ€™s changed - affecting how the culinary world views Russian cuisine.

Chefs now scan the cookbooks of Soviet years with an academic eye, finding lost and forgotten recipes and discovering new influences for their twenty-first-century menus. â€œRussians suffered 75 years, two-and-a-half generations, during Soviet time, fooled into eating grey, urban grub,â€ says Mukhin in his episode of Chefâ€™s Table. â€œI hate that period, it destroyed Russian cuisine. I will do whatever it takes to bring genuine Russian tastes back to the people.â€

What you are beginning to see is the clever manipulation of ingredients. Chefs are reinterpreting recipes; scouring markets, forests and oceans in their creation of patriotic plates; harnessing a single component and stretching and manipulating it with wonderful results. Ingredients such as mushrooms, cabbage, berries, honey and so-called peasant foods are being re-examined with menus centred on seasonal or storable produce. Lumb on plenty of caviar with that, and you're winning.

I think this might be my favourite cookie recipe to date. If youâ€™re looking for a rich, fudgy, crispy, chocolate overloaded cookie recipe then you have to try this!! ğŸª ğŸª ğŸª 
Double Chocolate (or you can do triple Choc) New York Cookies - Crispy on the outside, soft and fudgy on the inside, packed with chocolate in every bite. Perfect cold or warmed up in the oven for 5 minutes for an even richer melt in the mouth cookie! Did I mention I think I might love these?!? ğŸ¤ª

Recipe below ğŸ‘‡
230g - Unsalted Butter 
160g - Caster Sugar
160g- Light Brown Sugar
200g - Plain Flour
230g - Self Raising Flour
70g - Cocoa Powder 
3 Medium Eggs 
1 tbsp - Baking Powder
1/4 tsp - Bicarbonate 
1 tsp - Salt
450g - Chocolate chips / chunks 

Method: 
Beat the butter for 1 minute.
Add the sugar and beat for another minute.
Add the chocolate and beat for another minute.
Add the cocoa powder, flours, baking powder, bicarbonate and eggs and beat until it all comes together.
Weigh into approx. 125g balls.
Freeze for 2 hours.
Bake at 180C for 18-20 minutes.
Leave to cook for at least 15 minutes.
Then enjoy!!

Strawberry lemon pancakes on the menu this morning ğŸ“ğŸ¥ so light...so fluffy...so delicious!

Ingredients:
3/4c self rising flour
1c fat free plain Greek yogurt
1 egg
1T sugar
2T lemon juice
1/4c water
2 egg whites, beaten
1c strawberries, chopped

Directions:
1. Combine first six ingredients in a medium bowl
2. In a separate bowl beat egg whites until foamy
3. Gently fold the egg whites into the batter
4. Gently fold in the chopped strawberries 
5. Use a 1/4c to measure out batter onto a buttered skillet over medium heat
6. Cook 2-3 minutes per side, makes 9 pancakes

*** Jacket Potato ***
Â°
Â°
Â°
Jacket Potato was actually the first British dish I've tried many years ago and I absolutely love it since then!
It's cheap, easy to make, really tasty and you can fill it with whatever you like! ğŸ˜‹
My favourite filling is mayo tuna/mackerel and egg, but I enjoy baked beans and cheese too.

What's your favourite filling? â¤ï¸

Ingredients:
1 large baking potato
0.5 tsp. of olive oil
Half of tinned fish (tuna or mackerel in brine or in oil) 
1 hard-boiled egg
1 tsp. of mayo 
1 tsp. of Greek yoghurt 
1 tsp. of butter
Salt and pepper
Chopped spring onion to top and salad to serve (I've had Romaine lettuce, tomato, olive oil and spices) 

Method:
1. Preheat the oven to 200Â°C. 
2. Wash the potato, prick a several times with a fork and place onto the oven dish lined with baking paper. 
3. Rub the olive oil all over the potato and bake for 20 minutes. 
4. Turn down the oven to 180Â°C and bake for 1 hour, until the inside is soft and skin crisp. 
5. Cook an egg, peel it and chop (or use egg slicer if you have one). 
6. Split the potato in half. 
7. Scoop most of the soft inside into the bowl and add the drained tinned fish, egg, mayo, yoghurt and butter. 
8. Season well and stir until combined. 
9. Spoon the filling back into the potato skins. 
10. Top with spring onion and serve with a salad. 
11. Enjoy! ğŸ˜‰

MEAL PREPPING & MINDSET

Most of us want to get into better shape, lose weight or improve our health. But let's be honest.......we all  enjoy the exercise part because we get instant gratification. When it comes to food (notice I use the word food and not nutrition to keep it simple) as alot of us already find it challenging to consistently eat healthy and goal oriented. 

The good news is, once you experience the benefits and get into the routine of #mealprepping, you will never want to quit. 

The less good news is, there is no easy way. It requires will power and a strong mindset.

Here are some great benefits of meal prepping: 

- Save time
- Save money
- You will learn portion control
- It will help you lose weight
- Less stress during the week
- No food wasting
- Eliminates temptation to eat unhealthy foods
- You will gain will power to make appropriate food choices. 

Tip: I make sure all my groceries ğŸ¥•ğŸ¥¬ğŸ¥© arrive on a Sunday mornings, and I use my afternoon between 17:00-18:30 to prepp. Try it, you won't regret!

Delicious and flavourful Indian fish curry with onion-tomato base.
We Indians love to make complicated curries with lots of different spices. But this one is an easy recipe with only a few ingredients.
This is a very versatile ğŸŸ curry and will work with a variety of fish.

I always use mustard oil in my fish curries as it has a strong flavour profile and works well with fish.
While cooking with mustard oil, the oil is heated to a smoking point and then cooled before adding anything to it.This is done to reduce the pungency of the oil.
All you need is-

1. 1kg Katla/ Rohu or any other ğŸŸ 
2. Finely chopped tomatoes ğŸ… -3 
3. Finely chopped onions-3 
4. Cooking oil/ Mustard oil
5. 1tbsp ginger paste
6. 1tbsp garlic paste
7. 1/2 tsp mustard seeds
8. 1/4 tsp turmeric powder
9. Dry red chillies ğŸŒ¶-2
10. Roasted cumin 
11. 1tsp garam masala powder
12. Finely chopped green coriander( for garnishing). 

ğŸ  
Marinate fish with ginger-garlic paste, turmeric powder and little salt. Keep aside for 30min. Deep fry the fish pieces in mustard oil.

ğŸ  
On medium flame roast the dry red chillies and cumin and grind to a fine powder.
 
ğŸ  
Grind the tomatoes, turmeric powder and garam masala to a smooth paste.

ğŸ  
Heat mustard oil in a non-stick pan. Add the mustard seeds and let them splutter for sometime. To this add finely chopped onions, sauteÌ for sometime till they turn golden brown. Add the tomato and spice paste, let it simmer for a few minutes until the oil starts to separate. Add salt and  water to this and bring the gravy to a boil.

ğŸ  
Now gently add fish pieces to the gravy and leave it to simmer for 30 min.

ğŸ  
Garnish with finely chopped green coriander and serve hot with steamed basmati riceğŸŸ ğŸš

KIMCHI STIR FRIED RICE using @jyk_kimchi freshly made kimchi. I wanted a quick meal and decided to have stir fry rice.
Good thing about stir fried rice is you can add whatever you like.
.
I used the following.
Overnight white rice
2 beaten eggs
Diced homemade char sui (bbq pork)
Preserved packet veg
@jyk_kimchi kimchi (chopped) and the sauce
Fish sauce and salt & a it of msg (@mrnigelng )
.
Start frying the (beaten) eggs, then add the rice, stir it so the rice softens, then add the rest of the ingredients and then the seasoning.
Then serve.
.
Are you a stir fried person?
Share if you are a fan of quick meal.
15 mins quick meal
.

captions:
Vegetable Soup with Meatballs, Lentil and Orzo.
Followâ¡ï¸ @homerecipes101
Facebookâ¡ï¸ homerecipes101
-
-
-
-
-
-
INGREDIENTS
1 Lbs ground beef
1/2 Cup olive oil, divided 
1/2 Cup fresh Italian parsley, finely chopped, divided
1 Cup frozen vegetable mix
1/2 Cup onion, chopped
2 Cloves garlic, minced 
1/2 Cup potato, diced
1/3 Cup carrot, diced
1/2 Cup celery, diced
1/3 Cup yellow beans, chopped
1/2 Cup green beans, chopped
1/3 Cup brown lentil, rinsed
1/4 Cup orzo
1/3 Cup broccoli, cut into small florets
1/4 Tsp garlic powder 
1/4 Tsp onion powder 
1/4 Tsp cinnamon powder
5 Cups vegetable stock 
Water
Sea salt and pepper to taste

INSTRUCTIONS:
1. In a medium bowl add ground beef, 1/4 cup parsley, 1/4 cup olive oil, onion powder, garlic powder, cinnamon powder, salt and pepper. Combine well by hand. Form small ball shapes with your palms. Heat 1 Tbsp olive oil in a skillet then add meat balls and cook for 10 to 15 minutes turning them once or twice.
2. Meanwhile in a large pot heat the remaining olive oil and add onions, carrots, green beans, yellow beans and celery. Saute for 5 minutes, then add frozen vegetable mix, potato and garlic and saute for additional 5 minutes. Season with salt and pepper.
3. Add vegetable stock and water. Add enough water to cover the vegetables. Bring to a boil.
4. Add orzo and brown lentils. Reduce heat to medium and simmer for about 25 minutes, until vegetables are tender.
5. Add meat balls, broccoli florets to soup and simmer for additional 10 minutes. Add remaining parsley and turn off heat. Serve hot.

BEEF PULAO 

#nonveglover #easyrecipes #easycooking #instagram #foodblogger #foodbloggers #keralagram #keralacuisine #beef #beefpulao #nonveg #meat #meatlover #kottayamkari #foodiesofinstagram #foodporn 

Ingredients 

BEEF- 1/2 kg
Salt to taste
Pepper powder- 2 teaspoons
Vinegar - 2 tanlespoons
Ginger paste - 1 tablespoon
Garlic paste - 2 tablespons
Cinnamon- 1 stick
Cardamon - 2 pods
Cloves- 3 pieces 

Put all of this into a pressure cooker for 20 mins or till cooked .

Ingredients for PULAO 

Oil for frying
Onion- 1 thinly sliced
Green chilles - 3 
Tomatoes- 1 roughly chopped 
Basmati Rice - 1 cup
Salt to taste
Juice of 1 lime
Pudina leaves - 1/4 th cup
Corinader leaves - 1/4 th cup
Garam masala - 1 teaspoon 
Water

Method

1. Take a deep kadai and pour some oil . When its hot add the green chilles and fry for a minute. Add in the onions and fry till translucent.

2. Add the cooked beef , washed rice , diced tomatoes and mix well . 

3. Add lime juice and garam masala and add salt if required .

4. Pour in 1.5 cups of hot water. Add the pudina leaves and corinader leaves and cover and cook till rice is done . Add more water if rice isnt cooked , and cook again.

Done .. enjoy !!!

Open Steak Sandwich with Mushrooms and Peppercorn Sauce.

I love steak, I could easily eat it every day for the rest of my life.
This is my version of an Open Steak Sandwich with mushrooms and pepper sauce.
Itâ€™s super easy to make and can be put together in 20 minutes tops.
I start slicing up the mushrooms and shallow fry them in a drizzle of olive oil until they start to soften, I usually add a little bit of garlic, some chopped parsley and a splash of vinegar to add a bit of acidity.
While the mushrooms are cooking we can toast the bread and cook the steaks. For steak sandwiches I like to use Beef Fillet.
I cook it well seasoned with salt and pepper in a screaming hot pan 2 minutes per side, adding a little drizzle of vegetable oil.
Once the steak is ready we can rest it on a chopping board for a few minutes to let the juices redistribute throughout the meat.
At this point I add the peppercorn sauce to the mushrooms with the resting juice of the steak.
When the fillet is well rested we can slice it up, place it on top of the toasted bread and top with the saucy mushrooms.
This is literally all you need to do to get a super easy and tasty midweek dinner.

6 Tips To Make Fat Loss Easierâ£â €

â£â£â£â €
1) Chewing gum. A stick of chewing gum contains about 5 calories and it is a nice way to curb your cravings. Sometimes we just want to chew on something, so instead of going to the vending machine for a snack, we can just chew on a 5 calorie stick of gum. Also, minty fresh breath!â£â£â£â €
â£â£â£â €
2) Black Coffee. Black coffee contains caffeine, a natural appetite suppressant. Also, black coffee is great because it only contains 2-3 calories per cup. This number changes if you choose to add sweeteners or cream.â£â£â£â €
â£â£â£â €
3) Strawberries. Strawberries contain about 5 calories per berry and they are high in water. Water helps keep you full and the fiber will also benefit you greatly. Fruits / veggies, in general, are lower in calories and high in fiber.â£â£â£â €
â£â£â£â €
4) Sparkling water. Sparkling water is just water but the bubbly sensation makes us feel more full. An ice cold can of sparkling water is very refreshing and it doesn't contain any calories.â£â£â£â €
â£â£â£â €
5) Eat on smaller plates. This is a neat trick that people find helpful. If you eat food on a smaller plate and fill it up, your brain says "oh, this is a lot of food, it barely fits on the plate" â£â£â£â €
â£â£â£â €
6) Walk more. Going on walks and getting your steps up is a great way to lose more fat throughout the week. Walking is underrated and it actually burns a decent amount of calories. Going on walks during your work breaks or in the morning/afternoon can really be beneficial to clear your head and burn some more calories.â£â£â£â €
â£â£â£â €
I hope these 6 diet tips helped you out.â£â£â£â €

Countryvile - a nice walk in the countryside yet again disturbed by the lack of empathy and respect from the supposed guardians of it. A rotting corpse of a beautiful red fox hung in anger after a no doubt unnatural death. The disdain for these creatures so close to a sssi where they are valued is insipid of our farming communities. Overlooking a huge badger sett, one entrance had been half heartedly blocked by wood. The dairy farm adjacent seeped in slurry and the farmer had to get his tractor to scrape a path through it. I really cannot understand people who buy into dairy still. It is beyond the death of the cattle, the spread of btb and environmental disaster. Its given them a licence to wipe our iconic predators out. And their answer? "We feed the nation!" 

And we are extreme? Go Vegan. It takes nothing to be kind to an animal. Even less to choose a different carton of milk in the morning.

Tried & tested by: @sh4k33r4_recipes Mum
ğŸ“¸ Credit: Mum 

INGREDIENTS
6 tablespoon mayonnaise
1 tablespoon lemon juice
Â½ teaspoon salt
Pinch of freshly ground black pepper
2 sweet apples, cored and chopped
1 cup red seedless grapes, sliced in half or Â¼ cup finely sliced red cabbage
1 carrot (julienned)
1 cup chopped or coarsely crushed, slightly toasted walnuts
Mixed Lettuce Bag

***METHOD
1.) In a medium sized bowl, whisk together the mayonnaise, lemon juice, salt and pepper.
2.) Stir in the apple, grapes, cabbage, carrots and walnuts. Serve on a bed of fresh mixed lettuce.

*****INFO & TIPS*****

Some prefer their Waldorf salad made with yogurt, instead of mayo. I usually stay in the mayonnaise camp (which is what we are using in this recipe), but feel free to substitute yogurt for the mayo if you prefer. In which case you may need to add some honey to offset the added tartness of the yogurt.

No Bake Key Lime Tart. Thank you everyone for voting in my stories, on what dessert you would like to see today. The banana chocolate chip blondies were ahead up until the last hour.â 
â 
This is one of the desserts I lost the footage of that I remade a week ago. I made this dessert with two different crusts to see which one people preferred. Its funny, the crust votes were 50/50. Today I am posting the first way I made it which was with a gluten free graham cracker crust. I will post the cookie crust later on. This dairy free and gluten free dessert takes only 20 minutes to make and is so delicious!â 
â 
Ingredients for Crustâ 
1 box of gluten free graham crackersâ 
5 tbsp butter, I used a dairy freeâ 
â 
Add the graham crackers to a food processor and grind until fine. Melt the butter in the microwave, then add the graham crackers to the butter. Press into a tart tin and place in the refrigerator to set up.â 
â 
Ingredients for Fillingâ 
8oz cream cheese, I used a dairy freeâ 
1 tbsp coconut sugarâ 
2 8oz key lime yogurts, I used a coconut dairy free brandâ 
2 limes zestedâ 
1 lime juicedâ 
â 
In a bowl add all of your ingredients and with a mixer, mix until smooth. Pour into the tart shell. Enjoy!â 
â

Souropod, Staggeringly Good
Imperial Triple Fruited Gose, 7.4%
Confirmed vegan on Staggeringly Good website.

I've been waiting impatiently to try this one after seeing a lot of buzz- the promise of a fruity sour smoothie with a dinosaur on the can got me all excited, and has been sat in my fridge ready for this day.

Souropod TFG pours like juice, becoming smoothie-like by the end, without any head. It looks a bit like a swamp, with small bubbles popping on top as the fizz surfaces. It has a thick mango juice colour in the glass that looks like a, well, smoothie.

The first nose gives a strong sour mango aroma right off the bat. Going back for a second adds in the raspberry fruit and a delicate sea salt.

The first taste is an explosion of mango, tart berries,  citrus and a smattering of salt, all wrapped up with a sharp sourness, with some surprise smooth vanilla to finish it off. As you go your tongue adjusts to the sweetness, allowing the salt-bitter to really sing through before smoothing out.

This basically is a 7.4% sour smoothie, especially in the absence of any hoppiness. This is reinforced by the thick, juicy mouthfeel and persisting stickiness in the afterfeel.

I knew this one would be good, but I wasn't ready for just how good. It is incredibly drinkable - I kept having to remind myself to slow down before I guzzled the lot, especially at 7.4%. It deserved the hype, and now has a place in my beer highlights on VBR. I'll be sure to grab some more of this at some point, I'd encourage you to do the same!

@staggeringlygoodbeer

Method:
1. Preheat oven to 180 degrees.

PLANT-PROTEIN PROBIOTIC KALE SALAD ğŸ¥¬ğŸ¥—ğŸ’ªâ 
â 
i've been taking antibiotics for acne pretty regularly for about a year now, so getting in those healthy probiotics every day is a really important part of my diet. with the pickled onions, miso, and acv, this is truly loaded with healthy bacteria. plus, since i'm doing more strength training and running, the protein from the lentils and chickpeas means this salad truly hits all my needs! ğŸ˜¤ğŸ˜¤ i always feel so alive and âœ¨rejuvenatedâœ¨ after eating big ol' kale salad, and this definitely delivers 
â 
_________________________â 
â 
recipe:â 
â 
destem and chop one head of kale (save the kale stocks in your freezer to add to stir frys, smoothies, or more!). add to a large bowl.â 
â 
in a smaller bowl, add 2 tsp white miso paste, 1 tbsp of apple cider vinegar, 1 tsp maple syrup, 1 tbsp of olive oil, salt, and pepper. slowly mix in 1 tbsp of boiling water with a fork until the miso has dissolved and the dressing comes together.â 
â 
pour the warm dressing over the kale salad, and massage by hand for 2-3 minutes; the warm dressing will help soften the kale too!â 
â 
top with pickled onions (i used homemade!!), cooked lentils, chickpeas, and optional raisins for a bite of sweetness. enjoy!

Looking for a quick & easy vegan meal that you can prep ahead of time? This is perfect and can be done in minutes. â 
â 
Ingredients:â 
1. 4 oz grilled tempehâ 
2. 4 oz raw spinachâ 
3. 2 oz edamameâ 
4. 1 tbsp sweet mustardâ 
â 
Macros:â 
1. 316 caloriesâ 
2. 33g proteinâ 
3. 27g carbs (10 net)â

â 
To cook the tempeh - Preheat the grill to medium. If you've marinated your tempeh, remove it from the liquid and shake off excess. â 
â 
Place the tempeh cuts directly on the grill, and cook them, turning over once, until they are browned but not burned, and caramelized but not crispy; depending on the heat of the grill, this can take about 5 to 10 minutes total.â 
â 
This is perfect if you're currently cutting or want a lower carb, higher protein meal!â

âœ¨ A year ago âœ¨ Wanna talk about an inspiring start line - professional runners and the times they accomplish are amazing, something for all of us to look up to for what us humans are capable of, but where the bigger triumph lies for me is the women behind them balancing careers, families (especially moms - wow mad respect), and everything else life throws their way ALL while training and competing at a high level. âœŠ

This start line of 500 women was without question the smallest marathon start line Iâ€™ve ever been a part of, but I could feel womenâ€™s distance running and female sport in general being elevated so much in the buildup to and execution of this race. ğŸ™Œ

When I reflect on my journey to qualify, what I am most fond of is the bonds I formed with other women in pursuit of the same goal. ğŸƒâ€â™€ï¸ğŸ’— Supporting each other, strategizing together, cheering for each other, and lifting each other up when we fell a little short or completely bombed a race, and ultimately celebrating on February 29th, 2020 YEARS of hard work. ğŸ¥³ 

And to those who dreamed, committed & pursued this goal and didnâ€™t make it - my heart broke for them - it wasnâ€™t easy and I experienced first hand what it was like to miss by completely blowing up in one race and missing by 13 seconds in another. Qualifying isnâ€™t something I ever took for granted.

While we donâ€™t know what 2024 will look like, what I do know is we are sisters in sport and while we are each otherâ€™s competition, we can and should be each otherâ€™s biggest fans and supporters. Letâ€™s keep that momentum going! ğŸ¤—

TODAY IN OUR FIRST DETOX RECIPE: 

FIRE CIDER TONIC ğŸ¹â£â­ï¸
Infuse apple cider vinegar with horseradish, garlic, chiles, and ginger to make an immunity-boosting tonic that just happens to be delicious.â£
â£
YIELDMakes about 2 cupsACTIVE TIME20 minutesTOTAL TIME20 minutes, plus 1 month.â£
â£
INGREDIENTS:â£
â£
1 cup coarsely grated peeled horseradish (about 4 ounces)â£
1 small onion, coarsely chopped â£
8 large garlic cloves, smashed â£
1/2 cup peeled and coarsely grated or chopped ginger (about 3 ounces) â£
1 tablespoon ground turmeric â£
1 teaspoon black peppercornsâ£
4 rosemary sprigsâ£
1 whole cloveâ£
1â€“2 dried hot chilesâ£
1 lemon, quarteredâ£
2 cups (or more) unfiltered apple cider vinegarâ£
2 tablespoons (or more) honeyâ£
â£
SPECIAL EQUIPMENTâ£
â£
A (preferably glass) quart container; cheeseclothâ£
â£
DO AHEADâ£
Fire cider can be made 3 months ahead; store chilled in a (preferably glass) resealable container.â£
â£
PREPARATIONâ£
Place horseradish, onion, garlic, ginger, turmeric, peppercorns, rosemary, and clove in quart jar. Crumble chile (use 2 if you like it spicy) into jar. Squeeze in lemon quarters; add rinds. Pour vinegar into jar until solids are fully submerged. Cover tightly, then swirl jar gently to combine. Let stand in a dark spot 1 month.â£
Strain through a cheesecloth-lined colander or sieve into a large measuring cup; discard solids. Gather up corners of cheesecloth to extract as much liquid as possible (wear gloves if you wish to avoid turmeric stains on your hands). Rinse out jar and pour in liquid. Add 2 Tbsp. honey, then shake covered jar or whisk to combine. Add more honey to taste.â£
â£

Is there a better Sunday treat than fresh, warm, gooey cinnamon rolls? ğŸ˜ Maybe this Apple Strudel Cinnamon Roll Cake! Everything you love about cinnamon rolls, but add some delicious apple flavors and more of the best part of every cinnamon roll in every bite...the center! ğŸ˜‹
Check my â€˜Classic Cinnamon Rollâ€™ post on how to prepare the dough! Then turn it into this delicious cake!Happy baking and Happy Sundayâ¤ï¸
_____________________________

1 cinnamon roll dough 

Filling:
2 small tart apples, about 1.5 cups finely diced 
1/2 tbsp lemon juice 
1/4 cup brown sugar 
1/2 tbsp cinnamon 
1/4 tsp ground ginger (optional) 

Plus:
2 tbsp vegan butter, softened 

Optional: Simple icing made with powdered sugar and lemon juice 

Method:
Prepare dough the same way as for the classic cinnamon rolls.
Dice peeled apples very finely, toss them with lemon juice, sugar, cinnamon and ginger. 
Roll dough it into a large rectangle, spread a thin layer of vegan butter on it, followed by the apple mixture. 
Cut dough lengthwise into 3 long strips. Roll the first one up carefully into one large cinnamon roll. Place it on the end of the second strip, then roll it up as well. Repeat this step with the third strip, until you have one giant roll. 
Place that roll (filling side down) into a greased, round baking dish. Push it down gently to flatten it a bit. 
Let it rest and rise for 30 minutes, and preheat oven to 350 F/175 C in the meantime. 
Bake cake for 30 minutes, let it cool down, then drizzle it with icing. 
Cut, and enjoy!

Yep, itâ€™s fermentation again. This is three posts in a row now, but I swear I donâ€™t just sit in a corner eating sauerkraut from a jar. It just seems to be a process I really enjoy and a good lockdown activity. 

Typically made with pineapple skins, this is a Mexican drink. I always feel quite wasteful after prepping a pineapple since I compost all of the skin. However, this drink withdraws all of those otherwise lost flavours and nutrients, potentially (donâ€™t hold me to that).

Think of sweet pineapple, warming cinnamon, cloves and cardamom and spice from ginger. Other recipes I have seen also use chillis, however I gave that a miss this time. 
Itâ€™s quite a quick ferment, only a couple of days, so is only lightly carbonated but tastes fruity and spicy which is quite refreshing. It is currently chilling in the fridge because I think it will taste best extra cold. 

This recipe is from @dethample & @rivercottagehq â€˜Fermentationâ€™ book.

Today is National Rare Disease day! My name is Victoria and I have a rare disease called Ehlers-Danlos syndrome. Ehlers-Danlos syndrome affects connective tissue, primarily the skin, joints, and blood vessel walls. Symptoms include overly flexible joints that can dislocate, and skin that's soft, translucent, elastic, and bruises easily. In some cases, there may be dilation and even rupture of major blood vessels. There is no cure for EDS but treatment includes medication, physical therapy, and bracing joints. This is why you might see me with all different kinds of braces and mobility aids. Itâ€™s very easy for me to dislocate and sprain my joints day to day with simple tasks. Iâ€™ve had to relearn how to make my life work best for me and the way my body functions.

Fiber is a complex carbohydrate. It does not break down into glucose thus no calories! Two fiber types: (1) Soluble fiber = soft part of fruits, vegetables & certain grains. It slows digestion. That's good. (2) Insoluble fiber = tough skin of plant foods. Difficult to chew.  Relieves constipation. Most fibrous foods have some of each type of fiber.

IM NOT DRIVING TO LA SCALA RIGHT NOW CHOPPED SALAD

Ingredients:
Romaine lettuce
Iceberg lettuce
Shallots
Persian cucumbers
Garbanzo beans 
Fresh mozzarella or vegan cheese 
Pepperoncini peppers
Kalamata olives 

Chop lettuce finely. Bunch it together in one hand and then chop across. Repeat other direction for shredded lettuce. Chop cucumber, shallot, and pepperoncini into tiny pieces. Cut fresh mozarella into tiny pieces or shred. Rinse and drain garbanzo beans. To assemble salad: layer your lettuce, add the cucumbers, garbanzo beans, mozarella, shallots, pepperoncinis, and the kalamata olives on top. Finish with a light drizzle of the salad dressing below. 

Salad dressing:
1/3 cup olive oil
1/4 cup red wine vinegar
pinch of dried oregano
1 tablespoon dijon mustard
1/2 tsp fresh squeezed lemon juice 
Fresh cracked pepper
Optional: 1/2 tsp maple syrup

Salad dressing note: * adjust volume of each per your taste. Play with it. I hardly ever measure this.

Blended Flavors Chopped Salad ğŸ“ğŸ¥’ğŸ…

A Super QUICK - yet, totally unique chopped salad PERFECT for your weekend get-togethers by @cleanfoodcrush 

All the different Blended Flavors happening here in this salad are surprisingly phenomenal together!

If you prefer using different herbs or cheese - ANY type of crumbly cheese or herbs you have on hand will taste great!

Cucumbers are low in calories and contain a good amount of water and soluble fiber, making them very hydrating and great for weight loss and overall health.

Cucumbers are in the top 10 for high pesticides, and are on the Environmental Working Group's "Dirty Dozen" list, designed to help us quickly decide which produce should be purchased USDA organic. 

I recommend that the cucumbers you eat be organic, or local garden grown if possible.

This salad is best enjoyed within a few hours of preparing.

makes about 4 servings

Ingredients:
2 cups strawberries, hulled and halved
1 pint cherry tomatoes, halved
3 garden crisp cucumbers, chopped
1/2 small red onion, thinly sliced
a small handful of fresh mint, leaves picked
a small handful of fresh cilantro, leaves picked

Toppings:
4 Tbsps pine nuts
4 Tbsps crumbled feta cheese

Dressing:
1 Tbsp Dijon mustard
4 Tbsps extra-virgin olive oil
1 Tbsp raw honey
1 fresh garlic clove, minced
1/2 tsp sea salt
1/4 tsp ground pepper

Instructions:

In a small bowl add all dressing ingredients. Whisk really well, until emulsified.

In a medium bowl combine all of your prepped ingredients for the salad.

Drizzle your dressing and gently stir to coat.

Sprinkle with toppings and serve!

Enjoy!

Without electrical impulses, our hearts will not operate.
So, eat bananas for a happy and healthy heart.

HELLO AND GOODPIE

Ingredients:
1 box of simple mills pizza dough
Kalamata Olives
Mushrooms
Mozarella/cheddar cheese or vegan cheese 
Handful of fresh basil
Raos pizza sauce 

Make and bake dough according to box instructions in a cast iron pan. In the meantime, chop your mushrooms, slice olives, and shred your cheese and cut basil. Once pizza dough is done cooking, layer tomato sauce, shredded cheese, basil, mushrooms, and olives. Return to oven and bake for another 15-20 minutes till bubbly. 

Serve with spicy ranch dipping sauce. AKA: ranch that makes you dance. Posted on the grid.

ğŸ¥§Zucchini CakeğŸ¥§

Sometimes I struggle with adding enough vegetables to my meals. So I found a way to add some more of them. For example: you can use them while baking! Zucchinis in a cake make it more moist, delicious and healthy. And you can even make it with chocolate!ğŸ«ğŸ«
For the cake you need:
- 400 g grated zucchini
- 3 eggs
- 170 g raw cane sugar
- 3 tsp vanilla sugar
- 3 tsp baking powder
- 125 ml vegetable oil (I use rapeseed oil)
- 50 g unsweetened cocoa powder
- 300 g gluten free flour

First roll in the grated zucchinis in a kitchen towel and press till water comes out. Then beat the eggs with the raw cane sugar and vanilla sugar. Now add the other ingredients little by little.
At the end add the zucchini and stir them in the dough.Â PourÂ the doughÂ into a cake tin laid out with baking paper. Bake in a preheated oven forÂ 35-40Â minutes atÂ 180Â°C. Then turn onto a rack and leave to cool.

Right, this year I am going all out with the vegetable growing!!
Last year the vegetable growing was quite underwhelming; we had recently moved house so we didn't know where the best place to plant veggies in the garden was and we had a 5 month old baby. 

But, this year I'm on it! I love lists, so this tick sheet is perfect for me to track what and when I'm planting things. 

I've have loads of seeds left over and in date from last year so I don't need to buy much new. The only thing have bought are some seed potatoes. 

The weather has been glorious so far this weekend so I've planted as many seeds as I can indoors ready for transplanting outside once our vegetable growing areas is prepped. 

I have no idea what I'm doing by the way, but I wing it, and usually things turn out ok! I could spend ages reading up on how to grow things, but that is just not my style. 

Anyone else winging it at gardening?

GREEN SMOOTHIE WITH BROCCOLI

A super healthy green smoothie recipe with broccoli. Surprisingly good and refreshing healthy smoothie!

INGREDIENTS
1/2 cup broccoli
1 cup spinach
1 banana
1 apple
1 lemon
1 carrot

INSTRUCTIONS
Peel banana and lemon, wash, and chop the other ingredients.
Put everything in a blender and blend until smooth at high-speed.
Keep the smoothie in the fridge in an air-tight container and drink it throughout the day - as breakfast and at work at snack time.

Hummus Naan Wraps
4 pieces naan bread
1 cup hummus (I used roasted garlic)
4 cups greens (I used leaf lettuce)
4 T. feta cheese

Veggie Mixture:
1/2 cup cucumber, peeled and diced
1/2 cup red pepper, diced
1/2 cup red onion, diced
1/2 cup cherry tomatoes, quartered
2T. olive oil
1 1/2 T red wine vinegar
1/2 tsp Italian seasoning
1/4 tsp salt
1/4 tsp pepper
1/8 tsp garlic powder
1/4 tsp honey (optional)

Mix together all the ingredients for the veggie mixture.
While you are mixing the veggies together, warm or toast your naan bread.
Spread 1/4 c. hummus on naan.
Top with lettuce, veggie mixture, and feta cheese.

Options: add shredded chicken or garbanzo/other beans.
Change up the flavor with different kinds of hummus!

Bloat... weâ€™ve all been there! Check out this post from @bodysmartfitness on how you can beat the bloat.

ğŸˆBeat the bloat!â€‰â€‰ğŸˆ
â€‰
ğŸ¤°Bloating can put us in a right downer. It can derail our mood and make us feel like our efforts are going to waste. But could there be a reason why it's happening and could you combat it with these simple steps?â€‰â€‰
â€‰
ğŸ½ Eat Smaller Mealsâ€‰â€‰
Are your portions too big and your digestive system is struggling to cope? Try smaller portions and also be mindful of your eating speed to reduce that bloat.â€‰â€‰
â€‰
ğŸ¥¦ Cook your veggies don't eat them rawâ€‰â€‰
Raw vegetables can cause bloating for some people as they take longer to break down and have more bacteria on the surface.â€‰â€‰
â€‰
ğŸ¥˜ Make sure your fibre is in check â€‰â€‰
Are you eating enough fibre and helping your digestive system along? Get more fibre in your diet by eating things like cruciferous vegetables, rice, berries and beans.â€‰â€‰
â€‰
ğŸ’Š Probiotics & digestive enzymesâ€‰â€‰
You can get these in supplement format and they help with digestion.â€‰â€‰
â€‰
ğŸµ Drink hot water - tea - peppermint teaâ€‰â€‰
Soothing teas are always great for settling your stomach. We recommend peppermint teas and herbal teas. Try to go caffeine-free if possible.â€‰â€‰
â€‰
ğŸ’§Get a sweat onâ€‰â€‰
Go and workout and get that bloat down! Get your blood pumping and help your body process properly.â€‰â€‰
â€‰
ğŸ˜§ Check for food sensitivitiesâ€‰â€‰
There could be an underlying intolerance or food sensitivity causing the bloat. Speak to your doctor or use a food diary to track symptoms and see patterns.â€‰â€‰

Let's talk about @flashfoodinc 

If you've been following me for some time than you already know I'm obsessed with this app. Saving money on groceries? Thats right up my alley. 

Most people overlook this app, but it is one app that I cannot live without. 

Let's talk about these photos. In these photos I bought 4 mixed produce boxes. Altogether in these boxes there were: 
â€¢ a bag of organic lime 
â€¢ 3 bags of clementines 
â€¢ a clamshell of guava

â€¢ a bag of carrots
â€¢ a container of mushrooms 
â€¢ 2 packages of red thai peppers
â€¢ 1 package of green Thai peppers

Total retail of all this produce was $74.70.
I only paid $8.00! Which I saved $66.70. 

The best part was I only had to throw out a few clementines, 1 individual apple, 2 individual guava and the carrots i fed to my dads rabbits & chickens.

Loving how stocky these tomato seedlings are! ğŸ˜. Admittedly these are dwarf tomatoes (Tiny Tim variety) so you'd expect a stockier plant, but even standard tomato seedlings should be as stocky asÂ possible!Â Â 
.
.
Stocky tomato plants have a stronger stem which is crucial for supporting the plant as it grows.Â  A weak tomato will be too fragile to do well outdoors where it will have to contend with windy and exposed conditions.Â 
.
.
What causes tall and skinny ("leggy") seedlings? The main causes are insufficient light ğŸŒ or too much crowding ğŸŒ±ğŸŒ±. You can prevent leggy seedlings by ensuring they have enough high quality light right from the start.
.
.
But what about the seedlings you already grew that have turned out to be leggy? Is all hope lost? Nope!Â Â Last year I successfully rescued some leggy tomatoes with the following tricks:
.
1ï¸âƒ£ Adding more light ğŸ’¡(either add a grow light, or move to a sunnier location)
.
2ï¸âƒ£ Ensuring the seedlings are spread out enough so that they aren't competing with each other.Â  If there are multiple seedlings per pot then pinch out the weakest ones, leaving only the strongest seedling. (Try to avoid disturbing the roots at this stage)
.
3ï¸âƒ£ Repotting tomatoes and burying the stem up to the first set of leaves.Â  When a tomato stem is buried it will actually send out roots!Â  This basically buries the weak part of the stem and let's you try again ğŸ™ƒ As an added bonus this also increases the root mass - in fact many gardeners do this with all of their tomatoes!
.
4ï¸âƒ£ Turning on a fan for a little bit each day ğŸ’¨.Â  This mimics a natural breeze and will encourage the seedlings to grow stronger stems.Â  Just don't let them dry out as the fan will increase evaporation!
.
.

I read and listen to so many wellness materials like stoicism books, meditations, wellness podcasts, etc. and they all talk about living in the moment and not drifting out of it. â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €

ğŸ’šLately I was thinking about my journey to plant based / vegan lifestyle..

ğŸ¤” I never considered becoming vegan until one day it just happened.. 
 I knew a few people who were vegan, they had dogs or cats, loved their animals more than themselves. 
As I never had any pets, I was convinced that vegan lifestyle is not for me.

Later it came to me that vegan lifestyle is not about being a pet person.
One thing is whether you live with animals (which I still don't see myself doing, but who knows what the future brings) and completely another thing is being against violence and torture.

I might never come close to any animal (e.g. live in the same flat with animals), but what I know for sure - 
I am 100% against the treatment they get in those factories.

ğŸ·Animals deserve a better life.
ğŸŒNature deserves to flourish.
ğŸ™‹â€â™€ï¸And our body deserves to be nourished.

P. S. I just think, if there is someone out there, who thinks the way I used to think (that you have to be a pet person to adopt the vegan lifestyle) - that person should know = it is not true.

The aroma of this simple thai fried rice is an instant mood lifter!â‡ï¸â‡ï¸ğŸŒ¼ğŸŒ¼

Ingredients: 

2 cups of cooked basmati rice
1 cup basil leaves
1 small onion, chopped
1/4 cup babycorn
1/4 cup bamboo shoots (optional but add it for the authentic taste)
8-10 Tofu pieces, fried
2 chillies
1/4 cup red bellpepper
1/2 cup blanched brocoli
1 tbsp vegan fish sauce (recipe below)
1 tbsp soy sauce
salt per taste
1 tbsp oil

Recipe for vegan fish sauce :

Â½ tablespoon chopped garlic about 1 clove
Â½ tablespoon chili flakes 
Â½ teaspoon salt
2 tablespoons maple syrup
1 tablespoon lime juice
Â½ cup [125ml] hot water

Mix everything together in a bowl and store it in a container.

Steps:

1. In a pan, heat oil and add garlic, onions and saute well.
2. Add the bell peppers, bamboo shoots,babycorn and saute till the raw taste is gone.
3. Add the pan fried tofu, broccoli.
4. Add the vegan fish sauce, soy sauce  and the basil leaves and saute for 5 minutes.
5. Add the cooked basmati rice and salt. Mix everything together.
6. Turn off the flame and add the lemon juice and a few basil leaves to finish off.

captions:
How do you feel about sweets?

ğŸƒIt was August.  By that time, I had lost 5kg (2 what I had and 3 what I gained while I was changing food) I have a vacation, I leave and stop counting calories.  And so two weeks passed.  I gained 1-1.5 kilograms.  I knew that I had stopped monitoring the diet and it was not surprising to me that I typed.  My weight was below original weight, so I was quite happy.  I just started counting again.

 The weight fluctuated, but I insisted on my own and continued to eat already at 1800 kcal.  I haven't changed anything.  I ate fast food, ate sweets at night, ate various snacks, but everything was within the normal range of calories.  I did not observe proteins, fats and carbohydrates, because the main thing for me was to learn to eat correctly and exactly what I want.  By December, the total weight loss was -8kg.  I was happy.  I began to eat more, I had fewer inhibitions, during this time I allowed myself a lot that I had not allowed before, I finally felt comfortable.

THE RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN IRON AND HEMOGLOBIN ğŸ‘‡

Iron is a mineral that the body needs for growth and development. Your body uses iron to make hemoglobin, a protein in red blood cells that carries oxygen from the lungs to all parts of the body, and myoglobin, a protein that provides oxygen to muscles.

Deficiency in Iron leads to poor oxygen transport (anemia) as well as fatigue, depression, restless leg syndrome to name a few.

It's ideal to get Iron through food. Oysters, meat, chocolate, legumes, and spinach are a few sources.

It's all about balance!

Midweek ramen inspo! This one can come together quite quickly if you pay a visit to your local Asian supermarket ! 

 1) Tare - the flavour bomb that gives flavour and saltiness to your ramen . I used a soy sauce based one which is basically light soy sauce simmered with a splash of mirin and sliced ginger and garlic. 
2) Stock - here I used a veg stock that was made using dried shiitake, kombu, onion, ginger and garlic. But you can use any stock you get your hands on. Note: if your stock is salty, you will have to use less tare to avoid salty mess. 
3) Noodles - shop bough & boiled.
4) Toppings - couple of things I grabbed from my local Asian supermarket. Enoki  mushrooms and pak choi - blanched in hot noodle water to save time. Shop bought gyoza - panfried using fry-steam-fry method. Spring onion - chopped! 

Assembly is super easy - a tbs of tare for a medium size bowl ( I never measure but start low and add more if need to), couple of ladle-fulls of broth. Boiled noodles on top and whatever other toppings you desire ! Happy slurping!

#Homemade Dhokla Platter

#Dhokla ( à¤–à¤Ÿà¥à¤Ÿà¤¾ à¤¢à¥‹à¤•à¤²à¤¾ /  àª–àª¾àªŸà«àªŸàª¾ àª¢à«‹àª•àª³àª¾ )  is a #vegetarian culinary dish that is found mainly in the #Indian state of #Gujarat and parts of adjacent states. It is made with a fermented batter derived from rice and split urad dal. Dhokla can be eaten for #breakfast, as a main course, as a side dish, or as a #snack. 
.
It is very similar to #Khaman, however Dhokla is made of batter derived from mixture of rice and Urad dal, whereas Khaman is typically made from @Chickpeas gram and looks yellow in color. Khaman has become widely popular outside Gujarat but is misunderstood or incorrectly known as Dhokla.

Super easyâ€¦ Super Tastyâ€¦ Super Fastâ€¦

What you will need:

20oz. King Oyster Mushrooms per serving (as featured in vid)
tsp. Salt
Pinch Black Pepper
tsp. Garlic Powder
tsp. Smoked Paprika
Favorite BBQ Sauce ( I used @traderjoes KC Style BBQ )

After cleaning the mushrooms, gently shred the stalks with a fork beginning just below the cap. You can either save caps for another dish,  or chop up and add to your shreds. The caps will taste fine in your pulled pork, you just wonâ€™t have a completely shredded look, if thats what youâ€™re going for.

Add shreds to a pan on medium heat, add all the spices and stir. Cook until tender ( about 10 minutest ) then add your favorite BBQ sauce, and heat to desired eating temp.  At this point its time to put on a bun with your favorite toppings and enjoy. ğŸ¤¤ or you can eat with your favorite side.

Baked marinated and stuffed bell peppers
Very good reheated

A take on @howsweeteats recipe

Bell pepper
Mozzarella light
Red vine vinegar 
Garlic
Chili flakes
Salt
Bread
Garlic powder
Olive oil
Butter
Herbs

Drizzle bell pepper with olive oil and bake for 30-35 min at high heat
Whip the marinaded from the garlic, vinegar, salt and olive oil
Take out the peppers and drizzle with the marinates
Tear the bread
Heath some butter in a pan and fry the bread with some garlic powder
Stuff the peppers with mozzarella. 1 ball per serving
Bake a bit if you want the cheese to melt
Top with bread and the marinade
Sprinkle some herbs
Serve
